  <!-- HOW SHORT SQUEEZES WORK -->
  <section class="content-card" id="how-squeezes-work">
    <h2>How Short Squeezes Work</h2>
    <p>A short squeeze is a market phenomenon that occurs when a heavily shorted asset experiences a rapid price increase. Short sellers borrow shares and sell them, hoping to buy them back at a lower price. When the price rises instead, short sellers are forced to buy back shares to cut losses or meet margin calls — driving the price even higher in a cascading feedback loop.</p>

    <h3>Key Ingredients for a Squeeze</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>High Short Interest (>20% of float):</strong> Enough "fuel" — borrowed shares that must eventually be returned. The higher the short interest, the more buying pressure when shorts cover.</li>
      <li><strong>High Days to Cover (>5 days):</strong> A ratio above 5 means it would take over five days of normal volume for all shorts to exit. The longer it takes, the harder the squeeze.</li>
      <li><strong>An Unexpected Catalyst:</strong> Positive earnings, new products, buyouts, or massive retail buying can trigger the initial spike that forces short covering.</li>
      <li><strong>Low Float:</strong> Fewer available shares means each buy has a larger impact on price. Small-cap stocks with low floats are particularly susceptible.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Understanding <a href="/what-is-short-selling">what short selling is</a> helps contextualize why these mechanics matter. Short sellers face theoretically unlimited losses — unlike regular investors who can only lose 100% of their investment.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- HISTORICAL EXAMPLES -->
  <section class="content-card" id="historical-squeezes">
    <h2>Historical Short Squeeze Examples</h2>

    <h3>GameStop (GME) — January 2021</h3>
    <p>The most famous short squeeze in modern history. GameStop had short interest exceeding 140% of its float — more shares were shorted than actually existed. A massive wave of retail buying, coordinated on social media, sent the stock from under $5 to over $120 (split-adjusted) in weeks. However, 89% of retail traders who chased the squeeze lost money.</p>

    <h3>AMC Entertainment (AMC) — June 2021</h3>
    <p>Following GME's footsteps, the struggling theater chain had over 20% short interest. Supported by retail enthusiasm and a reopening economy catalyst, AMC squeezed from $2 to over $70, severely punishing institutional short sellers.</p>

    <h3>Clover Health (CLOV) — June 2021</h3>
    <p>During the retail trading frenzy of mid-2021, Clover Health became a target with high short interest. The stock squeezed from around $9 to over $28 in just days before rapidly declining — illustrating the extreme risk of squeeze plays.</p>

    <h3>Volkswagen — October 2008</h3>
    <p>The original mega-squeeze. Porsche quietly accumulated a 74% stake in VW while hedge funds held massive short positions. When Porsche disclosed its position, VW briefly became the world's most valuable company as shorts scrambled to cover. The stock rose from €200 to over €1,000 in two days.</p>
  </section>

