  <!-- METHODOLOGY & DATA SOURCES -->
  <section class="methodology" id="methodology">
    <h2>Methodology & Data Sources</h2>
    <p><strong>Short interest data</strong> was sourced from HighShortInterest.com, which aggregates FINRA and exchange short interest reports (last updated February 13, 2026). We included all stocks with short interest above 20% of float across NASDAQ, NYSE, and AMEX exchanges — totaling 76 stocks in our core rankings.</p>
    <p><strong>Squeeze Score data</strong> was aggregated from Yahoo Finance and SEC EDGAR filings for {studyMeta.totalStocksAnalyzed} US-listed stocks. Each stock is scored using our proprietary Squeeze Score — a 5-factor composite (0-100) weighing short % of float, days to cover, price momentum, short interest change, and institutional support.</p>
    <p><strong>Market capitalization</strong> was calculated from current share price × total shares outstanding. Price performance data was computed from historical closing prices via Yahoo Finance chart API. P/E ratios were sourced from StockAnalysis.com.</p>
    <p><strong>Update frequency:</strong> Monthly, aligned with FINRA's bi-monthly short interest reporting cycle. All data represents a point-in-time snapshot.</p>
    <p><strong>Data sources:</strong> Yahoo Finance API, SEC EDGAR, FINRA short interest reports, HighShortInterest.com</p>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">What stock has the highest short interest right now?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">As of early 2026, Groupon (GRPN) has the highest short interest at 46.06% of float, followed by Hertz Global Holdings (HTZ) at 44.41% and Better Home & Finance (BETR) at 43.93%. The majority of the most shorted stocks are in Health Care, Biotechnology, and Technology sectors.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">What does high short interest mean?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">High short interest means a large percentage of a stock's available shares (float) have been sold short by traders betting the price will decline. Short interest above 20% is considered very high and can indicate strong bearish sentiment — but it also increases the potential for a <a href="/what-is-short-selling">short squeeze</a> if the price rises.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">What makes a stock a good short squeeze candidate?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">A good short squeeze candidate typically has: (1) high short % of float (usually >20%), (2) a high days-to-cover ratio (>5 days), (3) a relatively low public float, and (4) a potential catalyst that could drive the price up unexpectedly. Our Squeeze Score combines these factors into a single metric. See our <a href="#squeeze-screener">screener</a> above.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">What is a good short ratio (days to cover)?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">The short ratio measures how many days it would take all short sellers to buy back their shares based on average daily volume. A ratio above 5 days is generally considered high — shorts would need significant time to exit, increasing squeeze potential. Below 2 days means shorts can exit quickly.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">Can short interest predict a short squeeze?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">High short interest is necessary but not sufficient for a squeeze. A squeeze requires: (1) short interest above ~20% of float, (2) a high short ratio, (3) a catalyst driving the price up, and (4) limited available shares. Most heavily shorted stocks actually decline — only a small percentage experience squeezes. See our <a href="#historical-squeezes">historical examples</a>.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">Do heavily shorted stocks outperform the market?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Not consistently. While short squeezes can produce dramatic short-term returns (GME gained 1,700% in 2021), the average heavily shorted stock underperforms the S&P 500 over 3-12 month periods. Stocks are usually shorted for fundamental reasons. The edge comes from identifying exceptions where the bearish thesis is weakening.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">How often is short interest data updated?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">FINRA requires broker-dealers to report short interest positions twice monthly — on the 15th and last business day. The data is published about 10 business days after, meaning it always has a 1-2 week lag. Daily short volume data is available from exchanges, but it's not the same as short interest (outstanding positions).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">What is considered a high short interest percentage?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">The average S&P 500 stock has roughly 2-3% short interest. Here are the thresholds: <strong>Below 5%</strong> — normal. <strong>5-10%</strong> — elevated. <strong>10-20%</strong> — high, significant bearish sentiment. <strong>20-30%</strong> — very high, squeeze risk escalates. <strong>Above 30%</strong> — extreme, historically rare. Compare with our <a href="/beta-volatility">beta & volatility rankings</a> for risk context.</div>
    </div>
  </section>

